  docker  vs vm
Based on the sources, here is a comparison table between Docker Containers and Virtual Machines (VMs) focusing on their core concepts and architectural differences:
Feature	
Docker Container	
Virtual Machine (VM)
Basic Definition	
An emulation of a user-space instance where processes run; a lightweight package containing code and its environment
.	
An emulation of a physical machine—including virtualized hardware—running its own operating system
.
Virtualization Level	
Abstracts operating system details from the application code
.	
Abstracts hardware details (CPU, memory, etc.) from the application code
.
Core Objective	
To provide environment consistency and lightweight portability across development, testing, and production
.	
To allow multiple operating systems to run on one physical machine to increase hardware utilization
.
Management	
Coordinated by the Docker Engine, which sits between the OS and the containers
.	
Coordinated by a Hypervisor, which sits between the physical hardware and the VMs
.
Architecture	
Shares the host kernel directly; containers only contain their dependencies
.	
Runs a full guest operating system and its own kernel for every instance
.
Resource Usage	
On-demand; requests only what is needed from the host kernel
.	
Fixed amount; occupies a specific amount of resources defined at startup
.
Security/Isolation	
Lower isolation; at risk if there are vulnerabilities in the host kernel
.	
Higher isolation; each application is buffered by its own entire guest operating system
.
When to Choose One Over the Other
According to the sources, your choice should depend on your specific application requirements:
Use Docker Containers for microservice architectures, rapid deployment cycles, lightweight resource needs, and situations requiring quick scalability
.
Use Virtual Machines for legacy applications, requirements for a specific older operating system, applications with substantial hardware needs, or when you need deep control over OS settings
.





